>>> babbling

may be practice for forming words

re-duplicative babbling first
    - bababa

variegated babbling next
    - baduga

manual babbling in deaf children
    - babbling w/ hand movements
    - repetitive movements that are confined to a limited area in front of the
      body similar to the sign-phonetic space used in sign languages
    - importance:
        many articulation tendencies of manual babbling transfer to the
        children's early sign production and then later into the production of
        words

>>> parsing the stream

speech is continuous ... but we hear discrete words
how do babies learn how words begin and end?

think of sausages
    - stream

statistical learning?
    - pattern perception rather than an innate biological grammar
    - ``hello pretty baby'' and ``pretty bird'' -> I kno what ``pretty'' means!

``motherese'' speech
    - exaggerated pitch contour
    - slower pace
    - exaggerated facial features -> enhance attention
    - repetition

>>> the reference problem

how does a child know to what a word refers?

whole object principle
    - if I point, I refer to the whole thing

mutual-exclusivity principle
    - if I know what an ear is, I know you're talking about head when pointing
      to ear and say head

categorizing principle 
    -> over-extension (see below)

joint attention
    - point = engage child to learn
    - attention on same thing

>>> early vocabulary

productive vs. receptive vocabulary
#    - you are in receptive control of the words that
        - you understand when you hear them or read them
#    - you are in productive control of the words that
        - you use to express yourself, in speech or in writing

words learned first
    - nouns before verbs (in English)
    - words linked to daily activities
    - labels of objects that capture a child's attention

