>>> fast mapping

rapid word acquisition

after 18 months, learn an average of |9 words per day|

>>> applying verbal labels

over-extension
    - applying verbal labels too broadly
    - ``dog'' for any four-legged animal
    - ``daddy'' for any adult man

under-extension
    - applying a label like a proper name
    - ``bottle'' only to refer to his or her own bottle

>>> wug test

kids know how to |apply rules| in language
    - even to nonsense words
    - a wug -> two wugs. I bot, I botted

other changes
    - syntactic complexity
    - pragmatics
    - vocabulary
    - disambiguation between subtle intonational differences
        - ``thats a hot dog'' vs ``I want a hot dog''

>>> nativism

nativism is the view that
    - certain skills or abilities are ``native'' or hard-wired into the brain at birth.

nativists argue:

since the ``poverty of stimulus''
    - language is too complex to be completely learned from input

there must be ``language acquisition device (LAD)''
    - theory: innate ability (brain struct) to language
    - recognizes basic rules in deep structure of the language

